<font color="#FF0000">THAT SACRED TRUST!</font><br>
<tt>Wed Jul 30 22:14:46 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I have not shared what I am about to share with many, not many would understand. <br>
Those that do, have been there and have had a chance to live again. They have a reverence for life, for all created things and honor men, made in the image of God. <br><br>
Prelude:<br>
Often early in the morning there was a time when those on radio watch were privileged to hear a different sound coming from their radios. It made no difference what frequency you were tuned into, or where you happened to be in South Vietnam. In the high mountains of a secured base camp or in the low valleys below. On a night ambush or in a small hooch, the sound would come from far away and it was unlike anything you've ever heard before and it was so very real.<br><br>
It wasn't everyday, but it was often, when the stillness of the night paused to take a breath, we would hear a song, a soft melody, pure and sweet and unlike any song, composed by men. A beautiful angelic song full of love, strength and endurance, hope, trust and faith. A song of deep love and shared thoughts and we all realized we were hearing something scared something not for everyone, but for us and for that moment and for eternity. <br><br>
If you heard it you would never forget it because you heard it first with your soul and then in your heart and finally with your mind. If by chance someone else was there at your side you would see the song, played in their eyes and in their tears that they could not and dared not hold back. With the song came great comfort, assurance, hope and trust, faith in tomorrow and acknowledgement that we were not alone. <br><br>
Dodge City, Quang Nam Province April 3, 1968 <br><br>
I always carried the M-60 machine gun in Vietnam, but Lieutenant Nowicki our 1st platoon commander had the men with the most experience walking point as we moved through Dodge City.  It was in an area where we often made contact and encountered heavy combat.  <br>
James Perry whom we called BaBaa followed behind me while the rest of India Company was spread out across semi-dry creek beds and flooded rice paddies. <br>
Perry was tall and thin, with long skinny arms and a large forehead. He was walking about 20-30 feet behind me as I stepped to the left of the wide trail we had been following. Then all of a sudden, time stood still. <br>
I was about to take a step forward when time stopped. I remember looking down at my foot and wondering, <br>
&quot;Why isn't my foot moving forward? Why is it taking so long for it to come down?<br><br>
It was then, that I realized the silence all around me. A unique silence surrounded me, as if I had entered into another dimension, a dimension without sound, without smells, without life, without time.<br>
Only my mind was functioning. Everything else in the world had stopped. Even my breathing had stopped. My heart stood still, time was standing idle, but my mind was taking it all in at once. A panoramic view and unique awareness of the whole area. Being conscience of this awareness startled me. <br>
I then heard the impossible, to my right I heard the hammer moving forward and striking the primer of a live round. I heard the primer ignite the powder that exploded inside the bullets casing and I heard the sound of rifling as the bullet turned inside the barrel and made its way forward. <br><br>
At about the same time I heard the exploding sound the bullet made as it cleared the machine gun's barrel, as it broke through the air, I felt two strong, powerful hands grab me from behind, from the top of my shoulders and backpack and pull me backwards. <br><br>
In that millisecond, time caught up with me and I saw my feet fly out and up from under me. As I flew backwards, twelve rounds of automatic machine gun fire shattered the palm tree that was in a direct line of where I would have been standing had my foot continued forward. <br>
I hit the ground with my back so hard that I bounced off its surface. The M16 rifle I had been carrying flew out of my hands and landed over to my right. I scrambled for cover as our right flank exploded with carbine, machine gun and automatic AK47 rifle fire. Grenades exploded up and down the creek bed where we had been walking. <br>
We were in an ambush and I was smack in the middle of the kill zone with incoming fire pouring in from several directions. <br>
As I grabbed my rifle and moved forward, I could see Perry flat on his stomach crawling toward me from about 35 feet away. <br>
When he saw that I was moving, he stopped and started firing toward the enemy. <br>
The enemies fire power was intense, it was coming in thick and fast, with grenades and claymore mines exploding all along the trail for about 30 feet. <br>
I opened up with my M16 on full automatic, and wished I had the gun.  By the time I slapped in another magazine the onslaught was beginning to die down. Just as quickly, the enemy broke contact. <br>
By the time, the rest of the company came around a bend in the trail they had moved out.<br>
I crawled over to where Perry was and wondered how he had moved so far away after he had pulled me back. Perry first loaded another magazine into his M-14 rifle, then crawled toward me. He met me half way. <br>
&quot;Hey, Babaa, thanks for pulling me back,&quot; I said.<br>
&quot;How did you know they were there? How you get so far away, after they opened up? Man you must have been flying!&quot;<br>
&quot;I didn't pull you back,&quot; he said.<br>
&quot;I saw you flying backwards as the bullets hit the tree to your left, I thought you were a goner. You're not hit? I thought, that was what had thrown you backwards. I didn't think you were alive. I was gona come get you, until I saw you move.&quot; <br><br>
I realized, he wasn't lying, he hadn't been near me when the firefight first started. I then remembered that seconds after the first rounds were fired I had turned to look in his directions and I had seen him flat on the ground about 35' away.  I remembered, even then wondering how he had gotten so far away from me in such a short time. But if it wasn't him, who had pulled me back?<br>
I knew then and even now, that someone had.<br>
Someone, somehow had pulled me back. The power and strength of those hands on my shoulders remains embedded in my mind. It was too real, too powerful to deny.  <br>
Divine intervention, in the jungle of Vietnam? Why? <br>
It would be years before I would visit those moments again and with each visit, I am more thankful and more fearful.  <br>
A little over a month ago, I found BaBaa again. We had not spoken in over thirty years. After we said our hellos, he said.<br>
&quot;Hey, Cookie, remember, that time when you were thrown back and thought I had pulled you............&quot;<br><br>
Those are my thoughs, I've shared them with you, may they change your life as they have mine.<br><br>
